      <h3>A child has a story <span class="it">long before</span> she has the words.</h3>

      <div class="body">
        <p><span class="dropcap">B</span>efore a child writes a sentence, she stages one. She walks a felt fox into the mossy cave, flies a butterfly across the lily pond as she mimics flying, lifts the Gruffalo into the wood and out again. Small World is the toolkit for that staging: hand-felted habitat mats that hold a scene, finger puppets sized for small hands, and circle-time story sets that turn a familiar rhyme into something a body can do. No screens. No instructions. Just landscape, character, and the long, generous space between them.</p>
